07725nam a22007695i 9780822388449DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20072006ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223884497 a10.1515/97808223884492doi  a(DE-B1597)553097  a(OCoLC)1224278831  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ1462b.S49 2006 7aSOC0100002bisacsh04a305.420972/090422200aSex in Revolution :bGender, Politics, and Power in Modern Mexico /cGabriela Cano, Jocelyn H. Olcott, Jocelyn H. Olcott, Mary Kay Vaughan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2007] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b4 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword: When Gender Can't Be Seen amid the Symbols: Women and the Mexican Revolution -- tIntroduction: Pancho Villa, the Daughters of Mary, and the Modern Woman: Gender in the Long Mexican Revolution -- tPart One: Embodying Revolutionary Culture -- tUnconcealable Realities of Desire: Amelio Robles's (Transgender) Masculinity in the Mexican Revolution -- tThe War on Las Pelonas : Modern Women and Their Enemies, Mexico City, 1924 -- tFemininity, Indigenismo, and Nation: Film Representation by Emilio ''El Indio'' Fernández -- tPart Two: Reshaping the Domestic Sphere -- t''If Love Enslaves . . . Love Be Damned!'': Divorce and Revolutionary State Formation in Yucatán -- tGender, Class, and Anxiety at the Gabriela Mistral Vocational School, Revolutionary Mexico City -- tBreaking and Making Families: Adoption and Public Welfare, Mexico City, 1938-1942 -- tPart Three: The Gendered Realm of Labor Organizing -- tThe Struggle between the Metate and the Molinos de Nixtamal in Guadalajara, 1920-1940 -- tGender, Work, Trade Unionism, and Working-Class Women's Culture in Post-Revolutionary Veracruz -- tWorking-Class Masculinity and the Rationalized Sex: Gender and Industrial Modernization in the Textile Industry in Postrevolutionary Puebla -- tPart Four: Women and Revolutionary Politics -- tGendering the Faith and Altering the Nation: Mexican Catholic Women's Activism, 1917-1940 -- tThe Center Cannot Hold: Women on Mexico's Popular Front -- tEpilogue: Rural Women's Grassroots Activism, 1980-2000: Reframing the Nation from Below -- tFinal Reflections: Gender, Chaos, and Authority in Revolutionary Times -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSex in Revolution challenges the prevailing narratives of the Mexican Revolution and postrevolutionary state formation by placing women at center stage. Bringing to bear decades of feminist scholarship and cultural approaches to Mexican history, the essays in this book demonstrate how women seized opportunities created by modernization efforts and revolutionary upheaval to challenge conventions of sexuality, work, family life, religious practices, and civil rights.Concentrating on episodes and phenomena that occurred between 1915 and 1950, the contributors deftly render experiences ranging from those of a transgendered Zapatista soldier to upright damas católicas and Mexico City's chicas modernas pilloried by the press and male students. Women refashioned their lives by seeking relief from bad marriages through divorce courts and preparing for new employment opportunities through vocational education. Activists ranging from Catholics to Communists mobilized for political and social rights. Although forced to compromise in the face of fierce opposition, these women made an indelible imprint on postrevolutionary society.These essays illuminate emerging practices of femininity and masculinity, stressing the formation of subjectivity through civil-society mobilizations, spectatorship and entertainment, and locales such as workplaces, schools, churches, and homes. The volume's epilogue examines how second-wave feminism catalyzed this revolutionary legacy, sparking widespread, more radically egalitarian rural women's organizing in the wake of late-twentieth-century democratization campaigns. The conclusion considers the Mexican experience alongside those of other postrevolutionary societies, offering a critical comparative perspective.Contributors. Ann S. Blum, Kristina A. Boylan, Gabriela Cano, María Teresa Fernández Aceves, Heather Fowler-Salamini, Susan Gauss, Temma Kaplan, Carlos Monsiváis, Jocelyn Olcott, Anne Rubenstein, Patience Schell, Stephanie Smith, Lynn Stephen, Julia Tuñón, Mary Kay Vaughan  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aFeminismzMexicoxHistoryvCongresses. 0aSex rolezMexicoxHistoryvCongresses. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzMexicoxHistoryvCongresses. 0aWomenzMexicoxHistoryvCongresses. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Feminism & Feminist Theory.2bisacsh1 aBlum, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRubenstein, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCano, Gabriela, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMonsiváis, Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCano, Gabriela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalami, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOlcott, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTuñón, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoylan, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStephen, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVaughan, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAceves, María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/